[1] Case update
Date: Sat 30 Nov 2019
Source: CMRE (Comite Multisectoriel de la Riposte a la maladie a virus Ebola) [in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://crofsblogs.typepad.com/h5n1/2019/12/drc-ebola-cmre-update-november-30.html


The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 29 Nov 2019:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 3310, of which 3192 are confirmed and 118 are probable. In total, there were 2202 deaths (2084 confirmed and 118 probable) and 1078 people have recovered.
- 341 suspected cases under investigation;
- 1 new case confirmed in North Kivu in Mabalako;
- 1 new death of confirmed cases; it was a community death in Ituri in Biakato;
- 1 cured person has been released from the Beni (North Kivu) Ebola treatment center [ETCs];
- no health worker is among the new confirmed cases. The cumulative number of confirmed/probable cases among health workers is 163 (5% of all confirmed/probable cases), including 41 deaths;
- Ebola response activities are paralyzed in the Mangina and Biakato sub-coordinations for security reasons.

News
Funeral mass in memory of the agent of the response deceased following the attacks of Biakato in Ituri
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- A Thanksgiving Mass was organized this Sat 30 Nov 2019 at the Saint Joseph Cathedral in Goma, capital of North Kivu Province, in memory of the Biakato Mines Subcommittee on Immunization Commission logistician in Ituri, Belinda Kasongo Kasonzo, who died as a result of the attacks that took place on the night of 27-28 Nov 2019.
- The General Coordinator for the Ebola Response to the Ebola Virus Disease, Prof. Steve Ahuka Mundeke, who presented the biography of the illustrious deceased, pointed out that the logistician who died at the age of 30, was a graduate in computer science management of the Higher Institute of Statistics "ISS Lubumbashi" and spent most of her childhood in Lubumbashi. She arrived in Kinshasa in 2018, where she was hired as a vaccine stock manager for the Expanded Program on Immunization (EPI), but long before she worked as an investigator at the World Health Organization (WHO) and as a Data Controller manager at the Provincial Health Inspectorate of Haut-Katanga.
- For the partners in the response, including WHO and UNICEF, Belinda Kasongo was a brave, courageous, and above all, a determined woman. She fell at the front, but the fight will continue until the end. They expressed their wish that the authorities would put an end to this unjustified violence.
- The coordinator of the Biakato sub-coordination, Fabrice Kadima, and all the teams returning from this part of the Democratic Republic of Congohave, have to this end, testified to the conviviality in which they lived with Mrs. Kasongo Kasonzo.
- At the end of the Mass, the remains were taken to Goma airport and repatriated to Kinshasa for the family funeral.

Vaccination
-----------
- A 2nd day without vaccination activity with the 2nd J & J vaccine following the disorders initiated by young people related to the security situation in Beni;
- 821 people were vaccinated, until Thu 28 Nov 2019, with the 2nd Ad26.ZEBOV/MVA-BN-Filo vaccine (Johnson & Johnson) in the 2 health zones of Karisimbi in Goma;
- since the start of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018 with the rVSV-ZEBOV vaccine, until 27 Nov 2019, 255 381 people have been vaccinated;
- approved on 22 Oct 2019 by the Ethics Committee of the School of Public Health of the University of Kinshasa and 23 Oct 2019 by the National Ethics Committee, the 2nd vaccine, called Ad26.ZEBOV/MVA-BN -Filo, is produced by Janssen Pharmaceuticals for Johnson & Johnson;
- this new vaccine is in addition to the 1st, the rVSV-ZEBOV, vaccine used until then (since 8 Aug 2018) in this epidemic manufactured by the pharmaceutical group Merck, after approval of the Ethics Committee on 20 May 2018. It has recently been pre-qualified for registration.

Monitoring at entry points
--------------------------
- Sanitary control activities [have been] in the Beni and Mangina sub-coordinations in North Kivu, as well as Mambasa and Biakato in Ituri following demonstrations by the population, decrying the killing of civilians and the attacks by armed persons who have targeted response teams;
- since the beginning of the epidemic, the total number of travelers checked (temperature measurement) at the sanitary control points is122 099 389;
- to date, a total of 109 entry points (PoE) and sanitary control points (PoCs) have been set up in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri to protect the country's major cities and prevent the spread of the epidemic in neighboring countries.

