- Fri 29 Nov 2019. Attacks
[Provinces 26 SARL; in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.provinces26rdc.net/rdc-6-morts-et-4-vehicules-incendiesattaque-contre-les-agents-de-loms-dans-lest/

DRC: 6 dead and 4 vehicles burned (Attack against WHO agents in the East)

According to the Center for Studies for the Promotion of Peace, Democracy and Human Rights (CEPADHO), the attack was planned by a group of Mai-Mai whose majority would come from Kabasha in the Beni territory (North Kivu). They would have split into small groups to distract the police. One section reportedly invested the base housing the response teams, while another raided the police sub-station of the square.

The militiamen who have invested the base of the response have successively killed 3 agents of the response, including Ms. Belinda Kasongo, assigned by the WHO to the Immunization Commission and 2 drivers attached to team 7 of the response in Byakato. In addition, they burned 4 jeeps of the response and a motorcycle, before sabotaging the tents, mattresses and other effects they accessed. Those who attacked the police sub-station managed to sabotage with bullets 2 guarded jeeps of the response. The intervention of law enforcement and security forces to put the attackers out of harm's way was not so easy. The exchanges of fire lasted until 7:15 am on the morning of [Thu 28 Nov 2019]. One Mai-Mai militiaman was killed and 4 others captured.

In addition, according to CEPADHO, the death of another civilian killed by the crossfire of the belligerents is deplorable. She was a woman known in the city as suffering from a mental illness and 3 other civilians were also reportedly seriously injured by stray bullets. In addition, other CEPADHO sources report a soldier who fell under enemy fire during FARDC [Armed Forces of the Democratic Republic of the Congo] intervention in support of law enforcement.

For the time being, although the army and police are in control of the situation after the Mai-Mai rout, activities have remained paralyzed in Byakato. Shops, the market, and schools have remained closed and traffic on public roads has been interrupted. Meanwhile, response teams evacuated their personnel, fearing for their safety, they say. The Monusco evacuated by helicopter the bodies and agents of the response teams that survived the attack. This is of greater concern to the inhabitants.

While these attacks are recorded in Byakato, in the neighboring village of Lwemba 4 community deaths have been reported, including 2 occurring on [Wed 27 Nov 2019] and 2 others on [Thu 28 Nov 2019]. A case would already be confirmed Ebola and other people should be sampled to know their condition before burial dignified and secure. A few weeks ago the Ebola response teams were forced to leave Lwemba after the multiple attacks.

At the same time, another attack aimed at sabotaging Mangina's CTE (Ebola Treatment Center) was barely prevented by the police. During the shootings with militiamen in Mangina, one assailant was killed and 2 others were captured that night. Early in the morning, in their search and search operations, the police still managed to get their hands on 2 other Mai-Mai, including one wounded, thus making a total of 4 captured.

WHO shocked by death of 4 Ebola response agents in Biakat
---------------------------------------------------------
Two attacks targeting Ebola response agents in the eastern Democratic Republic of Congo left 4 dead and 5 wounded. The attacks took place during the night on a Biakato "base" where the intervention teams live and in a coordination office for the Ebola response in Mangina (Ituri).

The dead include a member of the vaccination team, 2 drivers and a police officer. No WHO officer was among the dead, even though one of them was wounded. The other wounded are mainly agents of the Ministry of Health.

"I am wholeheartedly with the families and friends of these key players who have been killed in these attacks. We are doing everything in our power to ensure the safety of the injured and the front-line workers in the affected areas. These constant attacks must stop. We will continue to work with the DRC government, our partners and MONUSCO to ensure the safety of our staff and other health workers, " said Ms. Matshidiso Moeti, WHO Regional Director for Africa.

In the past week, the number of Ebola cases has dropped to 7, after a peak of more than 120 cases per week in April 2019.

