[Recommended reading:
M Ververs and A Arya. Ebola virus disease and breastfeeding: time for attention. The Lancet 394 (10201):825. 2019. DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(19)32005-7
https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2819%2932005-7
(...) Ebola virus has been found in the breastmilk of mothers in acute and convalescent phases of EVD from day 7 to day 26 after symptom onset, as well as in asymptomatic mothers (table). Data on long-term presence in breastmilk is limited and inconclusive. There was some discordance between Ebola virus in blood and breastmilk in 2o cases (cases 3 and 4), and possibly in a 3rd case (case 5), indicating that Ebola virus blood negativity is not sufficient to ensure safe breastfeeding in asymptomatic or convalescent mothers. Similarly, the current recommendation of testing breastmilk only in mothers who are known EVD survivors might be insufficient because asymptomatic lactating mothers in households affected by EVD have also been shown to have Ebola virus-positive breastmilk.

WHO 2018
https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/272716/WHO-VHF-2018.1-eng.pdf?ua=1
International meeting on persistence of Ebola virus RNA in semen and implications for public health
